Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility=20
News Release ( www.peer.org )

For Immediate Release: February 15, 2006
Contact: Chas Offutt (202) 265-7337

EPA CONTINUES TO SCREEN ALL INTERVIEWS WITH=20
SCIENTISTS =AD EPA Will Not Match =93Open Science=94=20
Policies Adopted at NASA and NOAA

Washington, DC =ADDespite growing concerns about=20
political interference with science, the U.S.=20
Environmental Protection Agency is requiring=20
prior headquarters approval for all=20
communications by its scientists with the media,=20
according to an agency email released today by=20
Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility=20
(PEER). EPA=92s stance of screening all press=20
interviews is at variance with recent=20
pronouncements of scientific openness by two of=20
its sister agencies, the National Oceanic and=20
Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) and the=20
National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA).

In a February 9, 2006 email to all staff, Ann=20
Brown the News Director for the agency=92s science=20
arm, the Office of Research and Development (ORD), admonished =96

=93We are asked to remind all employees that EPA's=20
standard media procedure is to refer all media=20
queries regarding ORD to Ann Brown, ORD News=20
Director, prior to agreeing to or conducting any=20
interviews=85Support for this policy also will=20
allow reasonable time for appropriate management response.=94

By contrast, less than a week earlier on February=20
4, 2006, NASA Administrator Michael Griffin sent=20
an all-employee email in which he committed the=20
agency to =93open scientific and technical inquiry=20
and dialogue with the public.=94 Griffin stated,=20
=93It is not the job of public affairs officers to=20
alter, filter or adjust engineering or scientific=20
material produced by NASA's technical staff.=94

Yesterday, in a Valentine Day message to all=20
staff, NOAA Administrator Conrad Lautenbacher wrote:

=93Our media standards also reflect an open policy.=20
We encourage our public affairs staff to keep=20
abreast of media interests. I encourage our=20
scientists to speak freely and openly. Dozens of=20
you every day are talking to the media and=20
providing the results of peer reviewed science=20
across a wide variety of NOAA topics. We ask only=20
that you specify when you are communicating=20
personal views and when you are characterizing=20
your work as part of your specific contribution to NOAA=92s mission.=94

=93Why are scientists at NASA free to answer=20
questions about global warming while their=20
colleagues at EPA are not?=94 asked PEER Executive=20
Director Jeff Ruch. =93Science does not come in=20
Republican or Democratic flavors; scientists=20
should be able to discuss findings without having=20
to check whether facts comport with management policy.=94

Scientists often fall outside the coverage of=20
whistleblower protection laws and thus,=20
scientists who violate agency gag rules may be=20
punished for insubordination. Corrective=20
legislation (HR 839 by Representative Waxman and=20
S 1358 by Senator Richard Durbin) that would=20
grant scientists the right to openly discuss=20
their findings is pending before both houses of Congress.

Ironically, at the same time that it is=20
restricting media contacts with scientists, EPA=20
itself is engaged in an aggressive public=20
relations effort called =93Science for You=94 that=20
promotes the importance of the scientific=20
research being conducted at the agency.

